WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.460
Good morning, everyone.

00:00:09.460 --> 00:00:14.600
So if you have ever used R Markdown before, you can probably recognize me.

00:00:14.600 --> 00:00:23.840
So since about 2014, I have created and co-authored a series of packages related to R Markdown,

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:30.580
like the R Markdown itself, and then 2016 bookdown, 2017 blogdown.

00:00:30.580 --> 00:00:41.320
So I'm responsible for a lot of things down, except the current government shutdown.

00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:54.119
So today I'm going to introduce a new member in the R Markdown ecosystem named pagedown.

00:00:54.119 --> 00:01:02.060
So this is joint work with an excellent collaborator, actually, I should say the best collaborator

00:01:02.060 --> 00:01:09.720
I have ever met in my life, named Romain Lustreau, it's a French name, sorry, I don't really

00:01:09.720 --> 00:01:15.599
I can't really pronounce that name precisely.

00:01:15.599 --> 00:01:20.639
So just before I get started, just a word of caution.

00:01:20.639 --> 00:01:26.699
This package is still very young, so I would treat it as experimental.

00:01:26.699 --> 00:01:30.639
So don't set your expectation too high.

00:01:30.639 --> 00:01:35.919
So after this talk, you may feel that, oh, this is great, so we can finally throw away

00:01:35.919 --> 00:01:44.160
LaTeX and Word, and unfortunately, the answer is not yet.

00:01:44.160 --> 00:01:46.760
There are still many rough edges.

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:53.760
Well, why do I choose to work on this pagedown package?

00:01:53.760 --> 00:02:02.120
So basically this pagedown just allows you to skip Word or LaTeX, but it basically creates

00:02:02.120 --> 00:02:06.559
paged documents from your web pages, like HTML pages.

00:02:06.559 --> 00:02:15.080
I personally have strong belief in HTML, like, basically sometimes I just say in HTML and

00:02:15.080 --> 00:02:23.000
the web I trust, so basically the reasons are, like, so first of all, HTML is very accessible

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:26.279
because you only need a web browser, right?

00:02:26.279 --> 00:02:32.080
Pretty much everyone has a browser, so the output from pagedown is an HTML page, so pretty

00:02:32.080 --> 00:02:37.919
much everyone can have access to that without installing any special software.

00:02:37.919 --> 00:02:44.720
And it's also very easy to embed interactive and rich media on web pages, and it's also

00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:48.759
much easier to parse HTML pages than PDF documents.

00:02:48.759 --> 00:02:53.759
For example, if you have a table on your HTML page, technically it's very easy to parse

00:02:53.759 --> 00:02:56.020
the data in the table.

00:02:56.020 --> 00:03:03.580
So the bottom line is that I think HTML and CSS will eventually catch up with LaTeX in

00:03:03.580 --> 00:03:10.020
typesetting, but it will be difficult for LaTeX or Word to catch up in other aspects

00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:14.660
of HTML, such as the interactivity.

00:03:14.660 --> 00:03:17.539
So the installation is pretty simple.

00:03:17.539 --> 00:03:23.419
So although I have released an initial version of pagedown to CRAN, I still strongly recommend

00:03:23.419 --> 00:03:29.220
you to test this package from GitHub, so you just install that from GitHub, and note that

00:03:29.220 --> 00:03:35.979
this package requires a higher version of Pandoc, Pandoc version 2, which is currently

00:03:35.979 --> 00:03:42.580
bundled in the preview version of RStudio, and because the output is HTML, and I would

00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:50.100
recommend you to use Google Chrome or Chromium to view or print the HTML pages generated

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:51.360
from this package.

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:54.279
So the usage is pretty simple.

00:03:54.279 --> 00:04:00.479
So if you're an RStudio user, you can just create a new RMarkdown document with the pagedown

00:04:00.479 --> 00:04:05.600
output from it through the menu file, new file, RMarkdown from template, and you can

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:10.160
find quite a few pagedown templates in that list.

00:04:10.160 --> 00:04:16.799
So for those who do not use RStudio, I'm not sure if you're aware of the name of this conference.

00:04:16.799 --> 00:04:20.320
But that's totally fine.

00:04:20.320 --> 00:04:21.799
You don't have to use RStudio.

00:04:21.799 --> 00:04:23.799
You can use any editor you like.

00:04:23.799 --> 00:04:29.880
So all the example or the template documents are in the source code of this package, so

00:04:29.880 --> 00:04:37.480
you can find them in the installation directory of your package or on GitHub.

00:04:37.480 --> 00:04:45.320
To preview the HTML output from pagedown, I recommend, like, for complicated reasons,

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:50.959
as Hadley would say, that the most reliable to preview a pagedown document is through

00:04:50.959 --> 00:04:58.899
the weird RStudio add-in named infinite moon reader, or equivalently you can call a function

00:04:58.899 --> 00:05:00.359
to preview it.

00:05:00.359 --> 00:05:05.839
And to generate a PDF from your HTML document, you can just open that HTML document in your

00:05:05.839 --> 00:05:10.279
web browser in Chrome and print it to PDF there.

00:05:10.279 --> 00:05:14.920
There's also a function named Chrome print in this package, but at the moment it doesn't

00:05:14.920 --> 00:05:17.279
really work perfectly well.

00:05:17.279 --> 00:05:20.399
So it will be improved in the future.

00:05:20.399 --> 00:05:25.320
And next I'm going to show you some of the output existing output formats and examples

00:05:25.320 --> 00:05:26.399
in this package.

00:05:26.399 --> 00:05:31.600
So the first one I would like to show you is the paged HTML documents.

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:36.839
So this is based on another JavaScript library named paged.js.

00:05:36.839 --> 00:05:43.480
This is basically a library to implement the W3C spec named paged media properties for

00:05:43.480 --> 00:05:44.480
CSS.

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:50.640
So basically it allows you to typeset your HTML pages through CSS, but the problem is

00:05:50.640 --> 00:05:58.040
that no web browsers really support that W3C spec, so paged.js did that job.

00:05:58.040 --> 00:06:04.799
So it implemented that spec so that you can view a paged document in your web browser.

00:06:04.799 --> 00:06:10.519
The name of the output format is pagedown colon colon HTML underscore paged.

00:06:10.519 --> 00:06:17.600
So just specify that as your output format and you click the knit button or use the infinite

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:23.000
moon reader and you will see a paged HTML document in your browser.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:30.799
This is just a screenshot created from the PDF generated in Chrome.

00:06:30.799 --> 00:06:35.200
So that is what a paged HTML document looks like.

00:06:35.399 --> 00:06:42.880
If you open the link here, pagedown.rbind.io, hopefully you can see that in your web browser

00:06:42.880 --> 00:06:46.720
that you've got a paged HTML document.

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:52.679
So in this document you can have things like the title page of your book, a table of content,

00:06:52.679 --> 00:06:55.519
several chapters, math equations.

00:06:55.519 --> 00:07:01.320
If your eyes are really good, you can probably see the running header on the fourth page.

00:07:01.320 --> 00:07:06.399
So you can have headers, page numbers, footers, all kinds of elements that you could see

00:07:06.399 --> 00:07:10.320
as you would see in a PDF document.

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:17.279
So besides creating paged documents, you can also create other applications like a business

00:07:17.279 --> 00:07:18.279
card.

00:07:18.279 --> 00:07:23.119
So on the left-hand side, that is just a full R Markdown source.

00:07:23.119 --> 00:07:28.640
So you can see there's title, author, output format, business card, and then the body of

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:29.920
your card.

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:34.799
So the output would be something like the picture on the right-hand side.

00:07:34.799 --> 00:07:42.720
So this is basically an unsolicited business card I made for Mr. Shiny, also known as the

00:07:42.720 --> 00:07:46.079
president of RStudio.

00:07:46.079 --> 00:07:49.279
You can also create a resume from pagedown.

00:07:49.279 --> 00:07:55.160
The output format is pagedown, colon, colon, HTML, underscore, resume.

00:07:55.160 --> 00:07:58.160
And R Markdown source basically looks like this.

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:05.760
So you can specify a sidebar in the aside part.

00:08:05.760 --> 00:08:08.760
So then you can have several subsections.

00:08:08.760 --> 00:08:10.760
You can have bullet lists.

00:08:10.760 --> 00:08:15.480
And in the main area, you can have an arbitrary number of blocks.

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:19.640
So like listing your education, working experience.

00:08:19.640 --> 00:08:23.920
So basically each block is a level 2 header.

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:29.679
And then inside each block, you can list the details about your resume.

00:08:29.679 --> 00:08:34.599
So that is what a resume produced from pagedown looks like.

00:08:34.599 --> 00:08:41.299
So if you click that link, you can also see a web page that looks almost identical.

00:08:41.299 --> 00:08:44.119
So by the way, this is actually a real resume.

00:08:44.119 --> 00:08:48.460
Although this is just an example in the pagedown package, this is real.

00:08:48.460 --> 00:08:53.460
So if you are looking for a Ph.D. student with strong computing skills and knowledge

00:08:53.460 --> 00:09:00.099
in bioinformatics, you may consider this person.

00:09:00.099 --> 00:09:04.200
And you can also create posters, HTML posters from pagedown.

00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:07.820
So currently I have included two poster formats.

00:09:07.820 --> 00:09:09.700
One is called Poster Relax.

00:09:09.700 --> 00:09:12.619
The other is called Poster Jacobs.

00:09:12.619 --> 00:09:14.320
So I will show you what they look like.

00:09:14.320 --> 00:09:16.580
So this is Poster Relax.

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:24.099
Well, actually this CSS style is borrowed from another package named Relaxed.

00:09:24.099 --> 00:09:27.299
It's not an R package, but a Node.js package.

00:09:27.299 --> 00:09:31.340
I only ported their CSS into pagedown.

00:09:31.340 --> 00:09:39.780
So yeah, hopefully you can see our lovely Carl Broman in the middle, smiling at you.

00:09:39.780 --> 00:09:44.419
So that is what a Relaxed poster looks like.

00:09:44.419 --> 00:09:47.539
And then we've got a Poster Jacobs.

00:09:47.539 --> 00:09:54.820
Yeah, basically I found this style on a LaTeX website.

00:09:54.820 --> 00:10:00.419
So I think this is probably very famous in the LaTeX community to create posters.

00:10:00.419 --> 00:10:06.380
So basically I saw that appearance, and I wrote all the CSS from scratch.

00:10:06.380 --> 00:10:11.919
In one evening, after my little kids went to bed, it took me about two or three hours

00:10:11.919 --> 00:10:12.919
to write CSS.

00:10:12.919 --> 00:10:18.340
The total number of lines of CSS is only a little over 100.

00:10:18.340 --> 00:10:20.039
So the CSS is really simple.

00:10:20.039 --> 00:10:26.960
And in case you are curious, the technique behind the CSS is called the CSS grid, which

00:10:26.960 --> 00:10:35.340
allows you to arrange elements on your posters on a grid.

00:10:35.340 --> 00:10:39.099
You can also write letters with pagedown if you want.

00:10:39.099 --> 00:10:42.979
So there's a format named HTML underscore letter.

00:10:42.979 --> 00:10:50.539
So as an example, I wrote a letter of recommendation for Amy Tanaka, who is a really cool hacker,

00:10:50.539 --> 00:10:52.700
I believe, in our community.

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:56.460
So the R Markdown source also looks simple.

00:10:56.460 --> 00:11:02.780
It's from me, to the hiring manager in the school of Ninja, the hacker's university,

00:11:02.780 --> 00:11:11.140
and the address is 404 North Front Road in the undefined city in an NA state.

00:11:11.140 --> 00:11:15.140
And then, yeah, the letter would look like this.

00:11:15.140 --> 00:11:20.020
So you can open that in your web browser and see the real letter.

00:11:20.020 --> 00:11:27.619
So actually, since this is just HTML, as I said, there are many advantages of using HTML.

00:11:28.619 --> 00:11:33.659
So for example, my slides are actually HTML, so I can embed the whole letter in my slides

00:11:33.659 --> 00:11:35.940
through an iframe.

00:11:35.940 --> 00:11:40.739
So you can see the letter live here.

00:11:40.739 --> 00:11:45.739
The one thing that I'm proud of this is that this is probably the first letter in history

00:11:45.739 --> 00:11:50.099
that contains a GIF.

00:11:50.099 --> 00:11:59.500
So this shows this GIF shows Amy's talent, and the last GIF actually is my description

00:11:59.500 --> 00:12:00.500
of Amy.

00:12:00.500 --> 00:12:06.859
She's such a just, like, such a cool hacker.

00:12:06.859 --> 00:12:11.280
All right.

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:17.460
So well, actually, despite of all these kinds of advances in technology, I feel a little

00:12:17.460 --> 00:12:24.460
sad that, I mean, we receive so many letters and e-mails every day, and we are no longer

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:28.099
excited like ten years ago, right?

00:12:28.099 --> 00:12:33.539
Ten years ago, you would be excited to receive an e-mail, and now you would be excited to

00:12:33.539 --> 00:12:37.780
receive a real letter.

00:12:37.780 --> 00:12:43.340
So besides letters, you can also write books with page down.

00:12:43.340 --> 00:12:50.059
There's a format named bookdown underscore CRC, which is a format for the publisher Chapman

00:12:50.059 --> 00:12:51.700
Hall CRC.

00:12:51.700 --> 00:13:01.500
So just to give you a quick overview, so this is what the book would like actually this

00:13:01.500 --> 00:13:02.500
is a real book.

00:13:02.500 --> 00:13:08.419
The bookdown book reproduced with CSS and HTML.

00:13:08.419 --> 00:13:10.320
Last I want to talk a journal format.

00:13:10.320 --> 00:13:17.679
So before that, I want to mention the talk from Catherine Mullen at the USAR 2014 conference

00:13:17.679 --> 00:13:25.239
where she mentioned the history and future of the Journal of Statistical Software, JSS.

00:13:25.239 --> 00:13:30.080
So that JSS was originally founded by Yangde Liu.

00:13:30.080 --> 00:13:38.119
So in Catherine's slides, she actually presented the original e-mail of Yangde Liu, where you

00:13:38.119 --> 00:13:40.799
can find his original proposal.

00:13:40.799 --> 00:13:42.799
So that was in 1995.

00:13:42.799 --> 00:13:44.400
1995.

00:13:44.400 --> 00:13:45.400
That was quite early.

00:13:45.400 --> 00:13:53.440
It was only a few years after I learned how to put on my own pants and stopped wetting

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:56.020
my bed at night.

00:13:56.020 --> 00:13:59.919
So in the proposal, he mentioned four points.

00:13:59.919 --> 00:14:06.479
He would like to create a journal that is electronic and freely available and then done

00:14:06.479 --> 00:14:10.479
in HTML and interactive and peer reviewed.

00:14:10.479 --> 00:14:12.799
I want to highlight two points in that proposal.

00:14:12.799 --> 00:14:15.880
So the journal should be done in HTML.

00:14:15.880 --> 00:14:22.119
And I would say that this is quite possible now because of page.js.

00:14:22.119 --> 00:14:27.840
And then the paper should contain interactive content, and that is also possible now because

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:34.280
we have interactive things like HTML widgets and shiny apps.

00:14:34.280 --> 00:14:41.799
So in fact, we have my excellent collaborator, Romain, has actually recreated the style

00:14:41.799 --> 00:14:46.960
of JSS through HTML and CSS.

00:14:46.960 --> 00:14:52.919
So I would like you to guess which one is HTML CSS and which one is LaTeX.

00:14:52.919 --> 00:14:54.479
It's hard to tell, right?

00:14:54.479 --> 00:14:58.520
It's just amazing, I should say.

00:14:58.520 --> 00:15:05.239
So last I want to digress a little bit in this technical talk to talk about something

00:15:05.239 --> 00:15:09.239
totally non-technical because I feel it is very important.

00:15:09.239 --> 00:15:17.000
So last year I read this book by Sigmund Freud, and I should say it heavily influenced me.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.219
Civilization and its discontent.

00:15:20.219 --> 00:15:23.760
Because I could relate this to many things in my real life.

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:29.719
Like PDF and its discontent, word and its discontent, typesetting and its discontent,

00:15:29.719 --> 00:15:32.799
journal publication and its discontent.

00:15:32.799 --> 00:15:35.820
There are just so many things I'm not happy with.

00:15:35.820 --> 00:15:41.359
So basically the main thing that he talked about in this book was the friction between

00:15:41.359 --> 00:15:43.799
civilization and the individual.

00:15:43.799 --> 00:15:54.400
And the friction is from the individual's instinctive freedom and the civilization's

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:58.119
demand for conformity and repression of instincts.

00:15:58.119 --> 00:16:03.719
So basically civilization is built upon control, beauty, hygiene, and order.

00:16:03.719 --> 00:16:09.400
If you look at these words, you may often think of your journal editor.

00:16:09.400 --> 00:16:13.320
Control, beauty, hygiene, and order.

00:16:13.320 --> 00:16:20.080
And in the last paragraph of that book, Freud said, so if you survey the aims of culture

00:16:20.080 --> 00:16:25.640
in Denver and the means that it employs, you would come to the conclusion that the whole

00:16:25.640 --> 00:16:28.080
effort is not worth it.

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:33.440
And the individual will be unable to tolerate the outcome of civilization.

00:16:33.440 --> 00:16:38.320
So I'd like to repeat, maybe the whole effort of typesetting is just not worth it.

00:16:38.320 --> 00:16:39.919
It's just not worth the trouble.

00:16:39.919 --> 00:16:44.400
Last year the quote that influenced me most was this, we become what we behold.

00:16:44.400 --> 00:16:47.640
We shape our tools and our tools shape us.

00:16:47.640 --> 00:16:50.919
Sometimes I just feel really confused.

00:16:50.919 --> 00:16:56.840
So when you feel confused, you can take a look at or you can hear what little kids say

00:16:56.840 --> 00:16:58.640
and observe what they do.

00:16:58.640 --> 00:17:05.359
So last Saturday I told my older son that I would come to this conference and give a

00:17:05.359 --> 00:17:06.599
talk.

00:17:06.599 --> 00:17:11.160
Because every day when I floss or brush his teeth, he would watch a video.

00:17:11.160 --> 00:17:17.180
So last Saturday I had him watch my last year's art student conference talk.

00:17:17.180 --> 00:17:20.959
And after he finished, so that was about block down.

00:17:20.959 --> 00:17:26.239
After he finished, his only comment was, I want to watch Bleepy.

00:17:26.239 --> 00:17:31.599
In case you don't know Bleepy, this is Bleepy and his garbage truck.

00:17:31.599 --> 00:17:32.599
So yeah.

00:17:32.599 --> 00:17:36.560
I thought my last year's talk was awesome.

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:39.319
Of course not as important as Bleepy.

00:17:39.319 --> 00:17:42.839
So just think about some journal typesetting guidelines.

00:17:42.839 --> 00:17:48.239
Like sometimes you are required to use code, SAM, preformatted keyboards, variable environment

00:17:48.239 --> 00:17:54.319
option command file, package, command package, URL, so many latex commands.

00:17:54.319 --> 00:17:55.719
Are they really important?

00:17:55.719 --> 00:17:56.859
I really don't know.

00:17:56.859 --> 00:17:58.479
And I doubt so.

00:17:58.479 --> 00:18:04.760
So sometimes you just as an adult, we just forget what our original Bleepy was.

00:18:04.760 --> 00:18:06.520
So why do we write journal papers?

00:18:06.520 --> 00:18:07.939
Why do we write books?

00:18:07.939 --> 00:18:09.560
To share knowledge, right?

00:18:09.560 --> 00:18:11.839
Why do we write letters?

00:18:11.839 --> 00:18:16.339
We show our care for our friends or family members, right?

00:18:16.339 --> 00:18:18.719
So will Markdown and CSS save us?

00:18:18.719 --> 00:18:19.719
Maybe.

00:18:19.719 --> 00:18:20.719
Because Markdown is very limited.

00:18:20.719 --> 00:18:25.719
But on the other hand, I believe it's very good to have constraints.

00:18:25.719 --> 00:18:29.099
So who is causing the trouble, actually?

00:18:29.099 --> 00:18:31.560
Is it humans or technology?

00:18:31.560 --> 00:18:33.760
Will CSS save us?

00:18:33.760 --> 00:18:34.760
Probably not.

00:18:34.760 --> 00:18:40.560
So sometimes in terms of working, I mean, the biggest tragedy is probably not that people

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:42.599
are lazy and they don't work.

00:18:42.599 --> 00:18:48.640
The real tragedy is that people are working extremely hard on trivialities.

00:18:48.640 --> 00:18:52.160
So just trivial things, like typesetting details.

00:18:52.839 --> 00:18:53.839
All right.

00:18:53.839 --> 00:18:58.880
I hope PageTime can save you some effort in typesetting, because I think HTML and CSS

00:18:58.880 --> 00:18:59.880
are just fantastic.

00:18:59.880 --> 00:19:00.880
All right.

00:19:00.880 --> 00:19:01.880
Thank you.

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:02.880
All right.

00:19:02.880 --> 00:19:03.880
Thank you very much.

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:04.880
Okay.

